  <title>Roots and Radicals</title>

<commentary audience="instructor"><title>Overview</title>
<p>In this Lesson we define powers of the form <m>a^{1/n}</m>, use the laws of exponents on such powers, and convert expressions from radical to exponential form and vice versa. Note that we do not yet consider powers with exponents <m>m/n</m>; those come in the next Lesson.  We briefly discuss irrational numbers and the roots of real numbers. Finally, we consider equations and power functions that involve <m>a^{1/n}</m>.</p>
<p>After introducing exponents of the form <m>1/n</m>, you might want to go over some of the Checkpoints in the text as a skills warm-up. Emphasize the difference between negative exponents and fractional exponents. Show students how to evaluate <m>n</m>th roots on their calculators using both radicals and exponents.</p></commentary>

<activity><title>Maximum Speed for Ships</title>

<introduction><p>When a ship moves through the water, it creates waves that impede its own progress. Because of this resistance, there is an upper limit to the speed at which a ship can travel.  This maximum speed, or hull velocity, is given in knots by
    <me>v_{max} = f(L) = 1.3 L^{1/2}</me>  
where <m>L</m> is the length of the vessel in feet.</p></introduction>

