<activity><title>Heart Rate</title>

<introduction><p>An animal's heart rate is related to its size or mass, with smaller animals generally having faster heart rates. The heart rates of mammals are given approximately by the power function 
    <me>H=f(m)=k m^{-1/4}</me>
  where <m>m</m> is the animal's mass and <m>k</m> is a constant.</p></introduction>

            <commentary audience="instructor"><title>Note</title>
            <p>Ask students whether they expect smaller animals to have slower or faster heart rates than larger ones, and what that means for the function <m>H=f(m)</m>. Then ask them how they know that <m>H=k m^{-1/4}</m> is a decreasing function.</p></commentary>

<task><p>A typical human male weighs about 70 kilograms and has a resting heart rate of 70 beats per minute. Find the constant of proportionality, <m>k</m>, and write a formula for <m>H</m> as a function of <m>m</m>.</p></task>

